Titanic Data Set: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Starting point: Make School Tutorial

Data set: Titanic - Machine Learning from Disaster

Notes:¶

  • I used the tutorial from Make School as a starting point and expanded from there.
  • I renamed the "train.csv" file to "titanic.csv" for simplicity and is found in the "data" directory. (Relative file path: "data/titanic.csv")
  • This analysis requires the following packages:
    • numpy
    • pandas
    • matplotlib
    • seaborn
In [ ]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Features (that need explanation)¶

Feature Definition Key
Survived survival 0 = no; 1 = yes
Pclass Ticket Class 1 = 1st; 2 = 2nd; 3 = 3rd
SibSp # of sbilings/spouses aboard int
Parch # of parents / children aboard int
Embarked Port of Embarkment C = Cherbourg; Q = Queenstown; S = Southampton

*Notes*:
Some children travelled only with a nanny, therefore $parch = 0$ for them.
Age is a fraction if less than 1

Remove unnecessary features¶

Because I am just looking at the data, some of the features are not necessarily needed.

Looking at "Age" and "Fare" Closer¶

In [ ]:
# Age Histogram
plt.hist(df['Age'])
plt.axvline(df['Age'].mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label="Mean")
plt.title('Distribution of the Ages of Passengers on Titanic')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xlabel('Age (in Years)')
plt.axvline(df['Age'].mean() + df['Age'].std(), color='orange', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label="Standard Deviation")
plt.axvline(df['Age'].mean() - df['Age'].std(), color='orange', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
plt.text(57,140, f"Youngest: {df['Age'].min()}\n" \
		 f"Oldest: {df['Age'].max()}",
		 backgroundcolor="lightgray")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Fare Histogram
plt.hist(df['Fare'])
plt.axvline(df['Fare'].mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label="Mean")
plt.title('Distribution of the Fares of Passengers on Titanic')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xlabel('Fare (in Years)')
plt.axvline(df['Fare'].mean() + df['Fare'].std(), color='orange', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label="Standard Deviation")
plt.axvline(df['Fare'].mean() - df['Fare'].std(), color='orange', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
plt.text(335, 575, f"Minimum Fare: {df['Fare'].min()}\n" \
		 f"Maximum Fare: {df['Fare'].max():.2f}",
		 backgroundcolor="lightgray")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Conclusion¶

Here, we can see that fares had a much larger variance than ages. This is also limited by the fact that a passenger can pay $500, but not live to be 500 years old.

/tmp/ipykernel_24096/766411463.py:2: FutureWarning: The default value of numeric_only in DataFrame.corr is deprecated. In a future version, it will default to False. Select only valid columns or specify the value of numeric_only to silence this warning.
  sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True)

Notes:¶

  • Highest positive correlation between sibsp and parch
    • This makes sense because families often travel together
  • Lowest negative correlation between Pclass and Fare
    • This also makes sense because lower class (e.g. 3rd class) tickets are usually cheaper than higher class (e.g. 1st class) tickets.
  • Age and Pclass also have a moderately negatively correlated.
    • Possibly because richer people tend to be older.

Probabilistic Analysis¶

Which features influenced survival the most?

"Women and Children First" Hypothesis¶

We found a correlation between Sex and Survival, but not between Age and Survival.

In [ ]:
# Women and children
w_c = df[(df['Sex'] == 0) | (df['Age'] < 16)]

# Survival Rate
# Normalize to get percentage over relative frequency
w_c_sr = w_c["Survived"].value_counts(normalize=True)
print("Survival Rate for Women and Children")
display(w_c_sr)

# Adult men
a_m = df[(df['Sex'] == 1) & (df['Age'] > 16)]

# Survival Rate
a_m_sr = a_m["Survived"].value_counts(normalize=True)
print("Survival Rate for Men")
display(a_m_sr)

In [ ]:
# Probability of children's survival
# Can also be seen in desciption table above Survived/mean
child_survival_probability = np.round(df[(df["Age"] < 16) & 
	(df["Survived"] == 1)].shape[0] / children.shape[0], 4)
child_survival_probability
Out[ ]:
0.5904

Observation¶

  • Only 15 percent of the passengers aboard were under the age of 18.
  • Only about 59 percent of children survived which is lower than the overall survival rate (61 percent), and the women-and-children survival rate (71 percent)
In [ ]:
# Probability of women's survival
women = df[(df['Sex'] == 0) & (df['Age'] >= 16)]
surviving_women = df[(df['Sex'] == 0) & (df['Age'] >= 16) & (df['Survived'] == 1)]

women_survival_probability = np.round(surviving_women.shape[0] / women.shape[0], 4)
women_survival_probability
Out[ ]:
0.7752
In [ ]:
# Probability of men's survival
men = df[(df['Sex'] == 1) & (df['Age'] >= 16)]
surviving_men = df[(df['Sex'] == 1) & (df['Age'] >= 16) & (df['Survived'] == 1)]

men_survival_probability = np.round(surviving_men.shape[0] / men.shape[0], 4)
men_survival_probability
Out[ ]:
0.1743
In [ ]:
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])
x_axis = ["Children", "Women", "Men"]
data = [child_survival_probability, women_survival_probability, men_survival_probability]
ax.bar(x_axis, data)
for i in range(len(x_axis)):
	plt.text(i, data[i] + 0.005, data[i], ha="center")
plt.title("Probability of Survival Aboard the Titanic")
plt.show()

Observation¶

Women actually had the best chance of surviving and children had a pretty good chance, but men did not.

  • Less than 1 in 5 men on the Titanic, ($< 20 \%$), survived
  • Almost 4 out of 5 women, ($\approx 80 \%$), survived.

Observation¶
